 ('13', '25', '5', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Shooting By The Seat Of Our Pants\",\"slug\":\"shooting-by-the-seat-of-our-pants\",\"postDate\":1408052606,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>A couple of decades ago, I was part of an agency team pitching a major new project to a very large technology company. In the interest of confidentiality I won\\u2019t use their actual name; I\\u2019ll just give you their initials&hellip;<\\/p><p>I B M<\\/p><p>Halfway through our pitch, it was clear we were pretty close to winning the business. In fact, they just had one real concern: were we agile and flexible enough to accommodate their last minute \\u201cstrategic changes in direction,\\u201d (aka: the whims of their senior management team)?<\\/p><p>Now this kind of objection is a classic buying signal. It generally means the client is truly interested. One of my colleagues recognized this fact and jumped on it immediately to try and close the deal. I could almost hear the wheels in his mind turning as he worked through two tried-and-true clich\\u00e9s. He later confirmed that what he intended to say was, either:<\\/p><p>A) \\u201cWe\\u2019re a company that likes to shoot from the hip&hellip;\\u201d<\\/p><p>Or&hellip;<\\/p><p>B) \\u201cWe\\u2019re a company that likes to fly by the seat of our pants&hellip;\\u201d<\\/p><p>What he actually said, however, was&hellip;<\\/p><p>C) \\u201cWe\\u2019re a company that likes to shoot from the seat of our pants.\\u201d<\\/p><p>Virtually the same words, right? Entirely different meaning.<\\/p><p>NOT a moment of perfect Clarity.<\\/p><p>We didn\\u2019t get that job.<\\/p><p>Clarity Matters.<\\/p>\",\"4\":\"\",\"8\":\"A couple of decades ago, I was part of an agency team pitching a major new project\",\"3\":\"\"}}', '2014-08-14 21:43:26', '2014-08-14 21:43:26', '182a2c58-35d4-48e0-b38b-c5edfdcf49bb'),
